HQphone: 404-463-3327
MissionStatement: The Atlanta Regional Workforce Board is a local partnership of business, education, labor and community leaders that achieves excellence by providing high-quality services that meet labor market needs of employers and residents. As the administrator for the Atlanta Regional Workforce Board (ARWB), ARC's Workforce Solutions Division provides workforce solutions for dislocated workers, unemployed adults and youth; and for businesses seeking qualified applicants. The Atlanta Regional Workforce Board's (ARWB) Career Resource Centers assist people seeking employment, training and education services. Funding for training through ARWB is provided for residents who live in, or have been laid off from their jobs in Cherokee, Clayton, Douglas, Fayette, Gwinnett, Henry and Rockdale counties. Young people, 14-21 years of age, interested in full-year youth programs funded by the Workforce Investment Act (WIA) must be low income and possess significant and defined barriers to education and employment.

MissionStatement: Our Houses Child Development Associate (CDA) program empowers and equips homeless participants with the skills needed to work in the growing childcare sector. We provide free training which enables participants to earn the national Child Development Associate (CDA) certification, which is currently the minimum requirement for any lead Pre-K teacher in Georgia. The CDA program consists of 120 hours of classroom instruction and 400 hours of a paid internship. While most CDA training programs take up to a year to complete, Our House has developed an efficient model which allows participants to complete the course in just five months. Partnering with other NAEYC accredited centers, Our House is training our future early childhood education work force.

MissionStatement: CPACS mission is to promote self-sufficiency and equity for immigrants, refugees, and the underprivileged through comprehensive health and social services, capacity building, and advocacy. CPACS, founded in 1980 on the belief that people need people, is the first, largest, and longest standing organization in the Southeast focused on issues concerning Asian Americans. Since its inception CPACS goal has been to deliver a broad continuum of comprehensive, family centered health and social services. During the past 33 years CPACS has evolved from a volunteer-run organization formed to help local Korean Americans, into a multi-service organization with a diverse staff of more than 25 full and 60 part-time employees with the ability to speak 15 different languages (Asian and non-Asian).

MissionStatement: Healthways Services offers a wide variety of health and human service programs designed to help individuals and companies achieve unparalleled professional success. Our prevention programs are called "Project S.T.O.P." (Self Taking On Prevention), we educate and encourage our consumers as they work toward self-sufficiency. The Project S.T.O.P. programs purpose is to provide assistance to families and individuals facing serious obstacles that affect their ability to live happy and successful lives or reaching their full potential. We seek to ensure quality of life, human justice and/or advocacy for individuals of all races, creeds, religions, ages, disabilities, nations of origin and sexual orientations. Our mission and vision is to promote the well-being and empowerment of families and professional communities through innovative, community-based multicultural health related services.

MissionStatement: To maximize employment opportunities and independence for individuals with disabilities. The Georgia Vocational Rehabilitation Agency operates five integrated and interdependent statutory programs that share a primary goal - to help people with disabilities to become fully productive members of society by achieving independence and meaningful employment. The largest of the programs are Vocational Rehabilitation (VR) Program, Disability Adjudication Services, and the Roosevelt Warm Springs Institute for Rehabilitation. Two other unique programs serve consumers with visual impairments: the Business Enterprise Program and Georgia Industries for the Blind.

Please be advised that you must be a current client of HOPE Atlanta in order to be referred to the Employment Supportive Service Programs offered at HOPE Atlanta.

MissionStatement: Atlanta CareerRise builds employer-led workforce partnerships in high-growth industries to fill jobs, close the skills gap and move underemployed individuals up the career ladder. Atlanta CareerRise benefits the community, employers and the underemployed by creating employer-led workforce partnerships to train employees and applicants for middle-skill careers in high-growth industries. This provides employers with well-trained, more productive personnel; moves employees into jobs with a sustainable living wage; and benefits the community by reducing the need for social services and increasing the tax base. Atlanta CareerRise, which is supported by private donors and grants and managed by the United Way of Greater Atlanta, is one of a network of regional funder collaboratives affiliated with the National Fund for Workforce Solutions.

MissionStatement: Emory Continuing Education (ECE) is Emory Universitys noncredit continuing education division. We extend Emorys ideal of the learning community beyond the core partnership of faculty and degree seeking / students by providing learning experiences to our neighbors. As guests on the campus, our students gain a personal experience of Emory University. We believe the love of learning should be a lifelong passion. Emorys continuing education courses serve self-motivated students, offering them the opportunity to learn and to empower and enrich their lives.
